{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568327"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:14:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:14:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20036"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20036"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.06,0.04,0.1,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12815"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115426"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12815"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20036"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97429"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3672"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11515"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11701"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"30263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48654"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115426"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic concerned about his health after the death of his horse. He lives on a rural property in southeast Queensland with fruit trees that attract flying foxes. His horse developed acute onset gastrointestinal disturbance (\u0022colic\u0022) and ataxia two days ago. The horse had not been vaccinated against any diseases in the past five years. The man reports that he administered medication via nasogastric tube to treat the colic and was in close contact with the horse\u0027s nasal and oral secretions during this process. Despite his efforts, the horse died 12 hours later. He is worried about whether he is at risk of any infection that he might have caught. The man has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Physical examination reveals no abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following diseases is this patient most at risk of developing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hendra virus infection","Leptospirosis","Rabies","Q fever","Australian bat lyssavirus infection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a concerning scenario of potential \u003Cstrong\u003EHendra virus\u003C/strong\u003E exposure. Hendra virus is a zoonotic disease endemic to parts of Australia, particularly Queensland and northern New South Wales. The virus is carried by flying foxes (fruit bats) and can be transmitted to horses, which can then transmit the virus to humans through close contact with infected body fluids. In horses, Hendra virus commonly presents with acute onset of neurological signs including ataxia, with or without gastrointestinal symptoms (as seen in this case). The man had high-risk exposure through close contact with the horse\u0027s respiratory secretions while administering medication via nasogastric tube. The mortality rate for human Hendra virus infection is approximately 60%, making prompt intervention critical. Management of high-risk exposures involves urgent consultation with public health authorities, consideration of monoclonal antibody therapy as post-exposure prophylaxis, and close monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeptospirosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a bacterial zoonotic disease that can be transmitted from animals to humans, commonly through contact with water, soil, or vegetation contaminated with urine. It commonly affects cattle, pigs, dogs, and rodents. In humans, leptospirosis commonly presents with sudden onset of fever, headache, chills, myalgia, gastrointestinal upset, and conjunctival suffusion. Severe forms can cause kidney damage, meningitis, liver failure, and respiratory distress. However, the horse\u0027s rapid neurological deterioration and death within 12 hours is more characteristic of Hendra virus than leptospirosis, which typically has a more prolonged course in horses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQ fever\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by \u003Cem\u003ECoxiella burnetii\u003C/em\u003E and is typically associated with exposure to cattle, sheep, and goats rather than horses. The primary route of transmission is through inhalation of contaminated dust or aerosols, particularly during birthing processes. The clinical presentation of the horse is not typical for Q fever, which primarily causes respiratory symptoms in animals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAustralian bat lyssavirus infection\u003C/strong\u003E is transmitted directly from bats to humans through bites or scratches, not via an intermediate host like a horse. While the patient\u0027s property has flying foxes, there is no history of direct bat contact. The risk is from the horse\u0027s secretions, which points to Hendra virus rather than Australian bat lyssavirus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERabies\u003C/strong\u003E is not endemic to Australia, which is considered rabies-free. While the neurological symptoms in the horse might be consistent with rabies in other parts of the world, this is not a realistic concern in the Australian context. The absence of rabies in Australia makes this an extremely unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention of Hendra virus includes vaccination of horses in endemic areas, avoiding horse contact with flying foxes by covering food and water sources, and keeping horses away from trees where bats roost. Personal protective equipment should be used when handling sick horses, especially in endemic areas. Any horse with suspicious symptoms should be isolated, and veterinary advice should be sought immediately with consideration of Hendra virus testing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hendra virus is a zoonotic disease transmitted from flying foxes to horses and then potentially to humans through close contact with infected horses.","Hendra virus in horses can present with acute respiratory or neurological signs, including ataxia and gastrointestinal symptoms.","Human Hendra virus infection has a high mortality rate of approximately 60% and requires urgent intervention."],"references":["Hendra virus control guideline. In: NSW Health [online]. 2023 [cited 2025 March 5]. Available at: https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/controlguideline/Pages/hendra.aspx#9","Hendra Virus. In: CDNA National Guidelines for Public Health Units, Communicable https://www.google.com/url?sa=t\u0026source=web\u0026rct=j\u0026opi=89978449\u0026url=https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/02/hendra-virus-cdna-national-guidelines-for-public-health-units.docx\u0026ved=2ahUKEwiwnK3fxfGLAxUaTmwGHeImGcMQFnoECBAQAQ\u0026usg=AOvVaw3PAVbvzHW9gwCu47XIqw4U","Middleton D. Hendra virus. Vet Clin North Am Equine Pract. 2014 Dec;30(3):579-89. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4252762/","NSW Health. \u201cLeptospirosis Fact Sheet - Fact Sheets.\u201d Nsw.gov.au, 2018, www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/factsheets/Pages/leptospirosis.aspx."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97429"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20036"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97429"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T17:13:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T17:14:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12815"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115426"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id